(2559, 'ESU', '地球科學系', 'ESU0037', '地球化學', '', 'COURSE OUTLINE\nThis course will be an introduction to the chemical processes that\ninfluence the solid Earth system. The application of chemistry to\nrocks offers important insight into igneous, metamorphic and\nsedimentary processes such as the differentiation of the Earth,\nthermodynamics, mineral formation and stability and the formation\nof mineral deposits. Further topics will include the use of\nradiogenic and stable isotopes in geochronology, the carbon cycle\nand life on Earth. The students will explore through a series of\nlectures and laboratory assignments novel methods which can help to\nunderstand the Earth’s natural environment. Assignments There will\nalso be 10 to 12 weekly assignments and a term paper which the\nstudent will give a supporting presentation. Text books\nGeochemistry: An Introduction by Francis Albarede, Second Edition\n(2009), Cambridge University Press, 342 pp, ISBN 978-0-521-70693-3\nPrinciples and Applications of Inorganic Geochemistry by Gunter\nFaure, First Edition (1991), MacMillan Publishing Company, 626 pp.\nISBN 0-02-336441-6 Weekly Lectures Week 1 Introduction to\ngeochemistry/Origin of elements Week 2 Chemical Differentiation of\nthe Earth Week 3 Properties of Elements (i.e. chemical bonding,\nionic radii) Week 4 Element Transport Week 5 Geochronology Week 6\nRadiogenic Isotopes Week7 Stable Isotopes Week 8 Mid-term exam Week\n9 Geochemical Cycles Week 10 Environments Week 11 Geochemistry in\nSedimentary Petrology Week 12 Geochemistry in Metamorphic Petrology\nWeek 13 Geochemistry in Igneous Petrology Week 14 Class\npresentations Week 15 Class presentations Week 16 FINAL EXAM', 0, NULL, 0, 0, 0, ''),
